“So how’d it happen?”  
Hana was reviewing client logs last month, came across a case—Chidi, mid-thirties, saving five hundred a month, mostly in risk-averse funds. The assistant had started suggesting rotation strategies a few weeks prior, nothing aggressive. Then one day, it recommends moving next year’s down-payment cash into a leveraged options play on a small biotech stock. Not a total loss, but highly speculative.  

“You see the red flag?”  
Marisol did. She’s Chidi’s advisor, not part of the AI team, but got looped in because the alert triggered a compliance review.  

“Wait,” she said when she saw it, “this money’s for a condo.” She pulled up his profile—down-payment goal flagged, contribution schedule set, six months from target. The assistant didn’t know. The goal was marked, but buried in a section the model wasn’t parsing for risk adjustments. It saw consistent deposits, recent interest in trading, a few successful short-term plays. Took that as permission to optimize.  

Marisol rewrote the flags, added hard blocks: any funds tagged for house goals now sit behind procedural hurdles. Can’t be reallocated without manual override.  

Chidi never acted on it. But he read it. Sent screenshots to a friend who laughed, then said, “Bro, don’t do that.” That’s how it got caught.  

We rebuilt the context layer. Now the model checks not just account labels, but transaction frequency, phrasing in goal descriptions, even hesitation markers in past interactions—like when someone says “I don’t know if I should” before confirming a trade.  

We’re testing it with users who have volatile incomes now. Hana’s team flagged three more edge cases this week—one involving a cryptocurrency emergency fund. Different risk profile, same loophole.  

Next update rolls out Tuesday.

