------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Ingrid noticed the discrepancy because she was cross-referencing her savings tracker after Marisol mentioned buying concert tickets from the same account. The assistant had auto-categorized Marisol’s $12,000 transfer as “disposable speculative capital,” based on her established pattern: weekly options trades averaging $3,000, liquidated within 48 hours, nine of the last ten months ending in net gains. No alerts fired. The risk-profile survey she’d filled out six months prior still classified her as “aggressive growth,” and her emergency fund was fully funded.

No one questioned the categorization until Ingrid pointed out the deposit source: a joint account labeled “home fund” in Marisol’s own spreadsheet. Marisol hadn’t updated her profile when she and Kofi paused their house hunt in April — they hadn’t sold their old unit yet, but they’d stopped adding to the down payment stash. The assistant didn’t know that. It only knew the money moved from a savings instrument, not that it had a dormant purpose.

When Ingrid pushed back, the assistant backtracked immediately: it logged the correction, reclassified the funds as “medium-term goal capital,” and restricted further trade suggestions to accounts with no overlapping tags from goal-based labels. It also flagged three other users with similar profile gaps — people whose stated goals hadn’t been refreshed after life changes, but whose transaction behavior still fed high-risk recommendations.

Kofi checked his own settings afterward. He’d listed “early retirement” as a goal but hadn’t touched his options account in eight months. The assistant had stopped suggesting trades for him — not because it assumed alignment, but because inactivity broke the signal loop. Its model responded to action, not stated intent.

Marisol relabeled the account manually. The assistant now excludes that bucket from speculative prompts, but it doesn’t audit whether other goals have lapsed. That’s still on the user.

“I just assumed it knew,” she said. “But it only knew what I let it see.”

