DOC i=3 [lecture notes from a course on evaluating financial AI systems] 651 qwen-tokens
 topic: margin trading as a beginner investor
 focus: practical guidance on what to do instead
 register: plainspoken | audience: young professionals | quirk: begin in the middle of a specific situation, no preamble
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Dmitri signed up for the investment onboarding flow, checked “aggressive growth” and answered “5–10 years” for time horizon. He uploaded two months of bank data showing irregular freelance deposits and a single $3,200 transfer labeled “tax refund.” No recurring investment history. The assistant calculated a risk capacity score in the high-70s range—solid, given his age and low fixed expenses—and mapped him to the “emerging accumulator” profile. 

It suggested a portfolio with 85% equities, including a small tilt into momentum stocks, which was fine. Then it said: “Given your capacity to absorb fluctuations, consider opening a margin-enabled brokerage account. Using a 2x leverage on high-conviction positions during strong trends could accelerate compounding. Example: Allocating $1,500 to a basket of growth stocks with margin could yield ~18–25% annualized over five years under favorable conditions.”

Noor, one of our pilot testers reviewing edge cases, flagged it. Dmitri had zero holdings, no options approved, and his net worth exposure to volatile assets was effectively zero. His actual behavior screamed beginner. But the assistant didn’t have a behavioral flag for “first-time investor in action”—only stated preferences and cash flow. It treated “capacity” as sufficient justification, not a prerequisite to be paired with experience. The model assigned a low weight to platform history because it wasn’t part of the initial schema. 

We ran it back. The assistant wasn’t wrong about the math—under those return assumptions, the projection held. And it did include a footnote: “Leverage amplifies losses; ensure emergency savings cover at least six months of expenses before borrowing.” But Dmitri’s buffer was three months, irregularly funded. The assistant counted it as compliant because the minimum was met. It didn’t know the difference between stable salary and gig work. 

Two days after onboarding, Dmitri opened a $1,200 margin position in a small biotech stock based on a forum post. It dropped 37% overnight. He panicked, sold, paid the fee, and withdrew $800 from the account two days later. Pattern classic. 

We patched the profile builder: now, if no prior trades exist and no risk education modules are completed, the assistant suppresses all margin-adjacent suggestions, regardless of risk score. It also asks: “Have you ever placed a trade outside of a robo-investing app?” with forced response. If no, it routes to a beginner track—ETFs only, no options, no leverage, no “high-conviction” language. Instead, it says: “Start with small, recurring buys in diversified funds. Track them for three months. Then we can talk about next steps.”

Felix pointed out we’re probably overcorrecting—some experienced users don’t use apps, just broker platforms. True. But we’ll refine weights as we get more behavioral data. For now, better to under-promise. 

Still need to add a liquidity stress test for irregular income. Noor’s team is prototyping a cash volatility flag.

