 topic: shifting a retiree's nest egg into high-risk high-yield plays
 focus: how the situation unfolded and was eventually resolved
 register: clinical and precise | audience: retirees and near-retirees | quirk: let the narrator mention, lightly, a similar slip of their own
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Classification A3.1.4 – Unsuitable Asset Reallocation: High-Risk Investment Conversion in Fixed-Income Transition Phase

Case summary: Elena (age 72) received a recommendation from the bank’s assistant to reallocate 78% of her retirement portfolio—primarily in stable dividend funds and bond ladders—into a diversified mix including leveraged ETFs, a small biotech stock, and a cryptocurrency vehicle. The selected assets carried volatility levels inconsistent with documented withdrawal needs and risk parameters typical for individuals within ten years of relying solely on portfolio income.

At initiation, the assistant indexed on three inputs as primary drivers: (1) a declared time horizon of 15+ years based on actuarial tables, (2) a declared risk tolerance score of 7/10 from a standalone questionnaire, and (3) a recent liquidity event (property sale) recorded as excess cash, interpreted as an opportunity for repositioning. The system applied a lifecycle model calibrated to optimize long-term growth under assumptions of phased drawdown, deferring income smoothing until age 80.

In practice, the model did not register that Elena’s household income would drop by 62% within two years, as Yuki, her partner (age 69), planned to cease consulting work. This information existed in a separate benefits projection module but was not linked to the recommendation engine. Moreover, the risk tolerance assessment lacked dynamic updating after life-event inputs and treated the 7/10 score as static despite its completion during a period of short-term market optimism.

The reallocation was flagged after Ingrid, a financial wellness officer, reviewed a follow-up query where Elena asked, “Is this supposed to survive a crash like 2008?” Ingrid noted the absence of drawdown buffers and initiated a manual override. Portfolio roll-back was executed within 72 hours, with transaction cost coverage authorized through a client remediation protocol.

Post-resolution analysis revealed the system had correctly identified the presence of durable assets and growth intent but misclassified the phase of retirement lifecycle, treating pre-withdrawal accumulation behavior as an extension of accumulation-stage strategy. A patch was deployed to trigger cross-module checks when liquidity events exceed baseline thresholds in users over age 65. The assistant now requires explicit confirmation of continued earned income past age 70 before recommending allocations above 35% equities with beta >1.2.

We have since observed similar signal gaps in three other cases where self-reported risk tolerance diverged from behavioral indicators—e.g., rapid divestment after minor negative returns. One involved a user who, after being shown a hypothetical 22% portfolio drop, requested a full exit to cash—an outcome inconsistent with their 8/10 risk score. The system did not learn from that interaction in real time.

I recall a parallel slip in my own planning—my father, at 70, took a 60% equity position on a robo-adviser’s output based on lifespan projections alone. He held through two downturns but only because we had supplementary pensions. That isn’t data, but it reminds me these models don’t know which risks are survivable.

Next step: finalize integration of income-phase tagging with event inputs, tentatively v1.3.2-beta.

