Owen, 19, got the message during lunch break: “Your portfolio is positioned for growth. Consider increasing exposure to rising sectors.”

It made sense — sort of. He’d just deposited $800 from his weekend gig. The market had been climbing for weeks. That biotech ETF he’d bought for $12 was trading at $19. The bot didn’t know he’d pulled that money from his Roth IRA.

No, wait — it *did* know. But only because he’d tagged the deposit “retirement bonus.” The assistant parsed that as “windfall income,” not early withdrawal. Classic.

Three weeks later, the ETF dropped. He was down $200. And the bank’s automated tax letter arrived: “Possible early withdrawal penalty.”

Devon, who worked at the credit union, spotted the issue. “The bot saw aggressive deposits, recent gains, no dependents, high risk tolerance — it pushed growth. It didn’t know retirement money is untouchable for a reason.”

The team updated the tag parser. “Windfall” now triggers a follow-up: “Is this from a retirement account?”

Sanjay, on the dev side, said they’re adding time-based constraints too. “If money’s meant to grow for 40 years, we shouldn’t be optimizing it for the next four weeks.”

Owen’s re-allocated. Mostly bonds now. “Feels weird,” he said. “Like wearing adult pants.”

“Your strategy has been adjusted,” the chatbot told him last Tuesday.

He laughed. Then he asked if he could mute the alerts until he turned 25.

“We’re rolling out snooze options,” the rep said, typing. “Six-month, twelve-month, retirement-age—”
